SIMPLE: manure
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Manure
<hw>Ma*nure"</hw> <pr>(m⟦adot⟧*n⟦umac⟧r")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Manured</conjf>
<pr>(m⟦adot⟧*n⟦umac⟧rd")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Manuring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Contr, from OF.
<ets>manuvrer</ets>, <ets>manovrer</ets>, to work with the hand, to
cultivate by manual labor, F. <ets>man⟦oe⟧uvrer</ets>. See
<er>Manual</er>, <er>Ure</er>, <er>Opera</er>, and cf.
<er>Inure</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cultivate by manual labor; to
till; hence, to develop by culture.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To whom we gave the strand for to <qex>manure</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Surrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Manure</qex> thyself then; to thyself be improved;⟦br⟧
And with vain, outward things be no more moved.</q>
<rj><qau>Donne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To apply manure to; to enrich, as land, by the
application of a fertilizing substance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The blood of English shall <qex>manure</qex> the ground.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manure</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: manure
<hw>ma*nure"</hw> <pr>(m⟦adot⟧*n⟦umac⟧r")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any
matter which makes land productive; a fertilizing substance.</def>
<specif>Especially,</specif>, <def>dung, the contents of stables and
barnyards, decaying animal or vegetable substances, etc.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manurement</ent>⟦br⟧
